My strategy is to address them sequentially, starting with the highest value component (TSP), followed by Steiner Tree and then CJS.
1. TSP: I will look for coordinates/distances and apply a heuristic like 2-opt or nearest neighbor to find a near-optimal Hamiltonian cycle.
2. Steiner Tree: I will identify terminals and edge weights, then use a Steiner Tree heuristic (like building an MST on the terminals' metric closure) to minimize the tree weight.
3. CJS: I will analyze the constraints and objective to find a feasible schedule that minimizes the cost/makespan as required.
I will allocate approximately 400 seconds per sub-problem to balance precision with the time cost of 0.01 pts/s.

